Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned in source.,"The source discusses both biological (bioprocess/biometallurgy: bioleaching, biosorption, bioprecipitation) and chemical/hydrometallurgical technologies (hydrometallurgy, pyrometallurgy) for REE recovery.","E-waste streams including consumer electronics (hard disk drives, computers), NdFeB magnet-containing components, phosphors, NiMH batteries, EV batteries, and wind turbine generators.",Examples cited: membrane-assisted solvent extraction demonstrated 95% REE recovery; HPMS/ hydrogenation yields alloy powder suitable for reuse; nanoengineered cellulose bioleaching reported 88.1% (Nd); biosorption using dried green algae reported 99.9% (Nd).,"Biorecovery: lab-stage predominately; Hydrometallurgy: pilot/commercial pilots (ORNL membrane-assisted solvent extraction piloted Aug 2022); HPMS/HyProMag: pilot -> commercial with production in 2023-2026 targets (HyProMag pilot produced 3,000 magnets in 2023; commercial production targeted 2024-2026).","Reported partners/grants include HyProMag with ERDF and German Ministry grants; ORNL working with licensee Momentum Technologies; EU projects (REEProduce, SUSMAGPRO) and university consortia like Valomag cited as collaborations.","Notable funding sources mentioned: European Regional Development Fund and German Ministry grants for HyProMag; U.S. DoD funding (~$45M) supporting domestic REE initiatives (e.g., MP Materials).","HyProMag: pilot produced 3,000 magnets (2023); commercial production targeted 2024-2026 and UK/Germany operations slated for 2025. ORNL/Momentum piloted membrane-assisted solvent extraction Aug 2022. Ames Lab process licensed to TdVib LLC early 2022."
