"Multiple entities mentioned in source: Rare Earth Salts (RES); Physical Sciences, Inc. (PSI); Inventure Renewables, Inc.; Marshall Miller & Associates, Inc.; Battelle Memorial Institute; Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory; University partners and others.",Not mentioned in source.,"Mixed technologies described in source: chemical/hydrometallurgical (electrowinning, acid digestion, solvent extraction, ion exchange/CIX/CIC) and biological (biosorption, biofilm-based airlift bioreactor).","Coal-related feedstocks and wastes: coal, coal ash, coal by-products, acid mine drainage (AMD) sludge, lignite, mine drainage.","Performance metrics from projects: target production ≥10 lb/day REOs at 90-99% purity (Marshall Miller project); PSI pilot: 0.4-1 tpd physical, 0.5 tpd chemical processing producing 50 g (≥10% REYSc) to targeting 500 g (≥20% REYSc); University of Kentucky reported >80% concentration and >75% recovery in lab tests; UND reported >2% concentrate and up to 35% recovery; WVU bench unit yielding 3 g/hr REE concentrate.","Most activities are at lab, bench, or pilot stages (Phase 1/Phase 2). Examples: Phase 1 feasibility studies (Inventure Renewables, Marshall Miller); PSI Phase 2 pilot-scale plant; LLNL biosorption project aimed at bench-scale airlift bioreactor demonstration.","Project partners and collaborators listed include K-Technologies, Pennsylvania State University, Texas Minerals Resources Corporation; Cumberland Mine Services, Minerals Refining Company, Outotec USA, University of Kentucky, Virginia Tech; Rockwell Automation, Tetra Tech, etc..","Funding listed are DOE/NETL awards for projects (examples): $1,250,000 for Inventure Renewables project; $8,750,166 for PSI Phase 2; NETL FWP totals $11,868,856 for program; $950,000 for LLNL biosorption project.","Recent (project) milestones in the portfolio include pilot-scale demonstrations planned or executed between 2016-2020, Phase 1 feasibility completions, bench-scale demonstrations (LLNL biosorption 2018-2021), PSI pilot plant operation targets, and techno-economic analyses to inform commercial design."
Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned in source.,"The source discusses both biological (bioprocess/biometallurgy: bioleaching, biosorption, bioprecipitation) and chemical/hydrometallurgical technologies (hydrometallurgy, pyrometallurgy) for REE recovery.","E-waste streams including consumer electronics (hard disk drives, computers), NdFeB magnet-containing components, phosphors, NiMH batteries, EV batteries, and wind turbine generators.",Examples cited: membrane-assisted solvent extraction demonstrated 95% REE recovery; HPMS/ hydrogenation yields alloy powder suitable for reuse; nanoengineered cellulose bioleaching reported 88.1% (Nd); biosorption using dried green algae reported 99.9% (Nd).,"Biorecovery: lab-stage predominately; Hydrometallurgy: pilot/commercial pilots (ORNL membrane-assisted solvent extraction piloted Aug 2022); HPMS/HyProMag: pilot -> commercial with production in 2023-2026 targets (HyProMag pilot produced 3,000 magnets in 2023; commercial production targeted 2024-2026).","Reported partners/grants include HyProMag with ERDF and German Ministry grants; ORNL working with licensee Momentum Technologies; EU projects (REEProduce, SUSMAGPRO) and university consortia like Valomag cited as collaborations.","Notable funding sources mentioned: European Regional Development Fund and German Ministry grants for HyProMag; U.S. DoD funding (~$45M) supporting domestic REE initiatives (e.g., MP Materials).","HyProMag: pilot produced 3,000 magnets (2023); commercial production targeted 2024-2026 and UK/Germany operations slated for 2025. ORNL/Momentum piloted membrane-assisted solvent extraction Aug 2022. Ames Lab process licensed to TdVib LLC early 2022."
